1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:24,000
 Hvaljeni su si Marija,dragi pratitelji YouTube kanala Udruge Hrvatska za život,Evo trenutno snimamo još jedan podcast život ovdje u crkvi Bezgrješnog srca Marijina na Jordanovcu u Zagrebu.

2
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:53,000
 u gostima nam je Ramona Trevino, ona je direktorica jednog dijela 40 dana za život iz Amerike, dolazi nam iz Teksasa, ima 47 godina, ona je supruga, majka i baka, a danas će nam posvjedočiti o svom životu, o svom velikom obraćenju sa pro-choice-a na pro-life, odnosno od osobe koja je bila za pobačaj do one koja je sada jako za život.

3
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 Ramona, da je vrlo.

4
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,000
 Oh, dvrlo, dvrlo.

5
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 Thank you so much, it's wonderful to be here in Croatia.

6
00:00:58,000 --> 00:00:59,000
 Thank you.

7
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:03,000
 Can you please tell us about your roles now in your life?

8
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,000
 Who is Ramona at this moment?

9
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 Oh, who is Ramona at this moment?

10
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:32,000
 Well, I am a wife, I'm a mother, I'm a grandmother, so that's my primary role and I'm currently working as the director of outreach for the 40 days for life national team back home in Texas and just continue to promote life and try to balance my work in the pro-life efforts with my most important work, which is that of a mother and a grandmother and a wife.

11
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:37,000
 And what does it mean, director of outreach? What do you do?

12
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
 I would love to know as well.

13
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:57,000
 Well, as director of outreach part of my role is to continue to promote 40 days for life, to encourage our leaders, encourage more volunteers, just really to try to go out and bring more people into the fold of 40 days for life.

14
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
 That's really the simplest answer, yes.

15
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 Thank you so very much for coming here in Croatia.

16
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:12,000
 We have our seventh international conference, Now Choose Life, and you are here as our guest.

17
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 So we are very thankful and grateful to have you here.

18
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
 Well, I'm extremely grateful to be here with you.

19
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:26,000
 Can you please tell us something about your childhood, your religious background, your family and everything?

20
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 Yes, so I was baptized as a Catholic when we were babies, my sister and I am the youngest of two.

21
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 And I would call our family more cultural Catholic.

22
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 We weren't really faithful in the terms of living out our Catholic faith.

23
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 So my mom and dad were both married in the Catholic Church, but we weren't really raised with any faith formation.

24
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 So the only sacrament I received was baptism.

25
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 And we practiced in the sense that culturally we embraced the things of Catholicism.

26
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:13,000
 So, you know, having rosaries and maybe on occasion, you know, praying rosaries, images, religious images, mostly of Our Lady of Guadalupe was very prominent.

27
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 And just really just celebrating Easter, Christmas, and we practiced Lent as well.

28
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 So we followed Lenten practices of abstaining from meat on Fridays and giving up things during Lent and things like that.

29
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
 But I didn't really have the formation and the understanding of why.

30
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 So we did it, but we never knew why we did it as children, you know, and my parents never really talked about that or discussed that.

31
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:47,000
 And it could be that they failed themselves to really understand their faith.

32
00:03:47,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 But I think it was despite not having that formation, I think having some of that in my life was very instrumental in really having the grace that ultimately, you know, led to my full conversion back to my faith.

33
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:16,000
 As you know, I used to work for Planned Parenthood, but before all of that, I was pregnant at 16 years old.

34
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:28,000
 And it was quite a shock to my family, but it was also, I was also extremely blessed that my parents never considered abortion for me.

35
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 And I never considered abortion for myself. So being pro-life, even though it like, well, we never talked about abortion in our family.

36
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 It just wasn't a subject that we talked about, even though it was very, very legal in the United States.

37
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:55,000
 But during that time in the 90s, when I became pregnant, you know, it just wasn't something that we talked about.

38
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 And so I think just naturally, when I became pregnant, I knew, you know, that I was a mom in that moment.

39
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 So it never was a thought. And I was very blessed because my parents never suggested it to me, especially considering that I was so young.

40
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 And oftentimes we see a lot of young girls who whose parents are the ones who often pressure them to have abortions.

41
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 But I was in a very abusive relationship with the father of my daughter, very toxic and unhealthy relationship.

42
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 And I was in that for eight years before I finally left, you know, and found the courage to face life alone as a single mother.

43
00:05:43,000 --> 00:06:02,000
 And my faith, even though I didn't really practice it, played such a huge role in being able to really see that God wanted more for me, that this was not part of his plan for me to be in that type of situation and especially wanted more for my daughter.

44
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 And so I got out of that relationship and praise be to God, I would it would lead me to my now husband of 18 years.

45
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 And what did you do? How did you manage your life with a child, with school? How did your friends react of that news and everything? How was that?

46
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 Yeah, so I was a really good student. I made really good grades in school. And when I became pregnant, everyone said I ruined my life.

47
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 You know, that was the talk of the town. And so I come from a very I live still in my hometown, but it's a very small town.

48
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 of around a thousand people. And so everyone knows everyone, you know, and when you are in a school where everyone literally knows everybody and you're pregnant, you can imagine the scandal.

49
00:06:54,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 And I was going to school pregnant. So I was very young and I went to school pregnant and and everyone, you know, whispered behind my back that I had ruined my life, you know, and that I had so much going for me.

50
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:25,000
 And now what was I going to do? Right. But I ended up quitting high school and I just couldn't handle not just the pressure from school, but also the emotional abuse that I was going through at home with my the father of my daughter.

51
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 So there was a lot of things that were going on behind the scenes. And I ended up, you know, quitting school and just going to work in the workforce and trying to raise my daughter and support my daughter.

52
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 And again, I'm so grateful to my mom and dad because they they were there still supporting me. They never kicked me out of the house or anything like that. We were they were there.

53
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 And blessed to have parents who were so supportive and they had their own problems. My dad was an alcoholic for most of my life. He's passed away now. But but for the majority of of his life and my life, he was an alcoholic.

54
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:21,000
 But despite the troubles that my mom and dad had in their marriage and obviously my father's alcoholism, they loved me and they loved my sister and they loved their granddaughter.

55
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:34,000
 And they were always very supportive of life and of their daughter, you know, daughter's choice to have this baby. And so for that, I'm very, very grateful.

56
00:08:34,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 We talked last night about love and marriage and how many people just young people just don't believe in marriage in these days. And I think if you had your primary family who is very good, who is married and who are together despite of everything that they have problems and everything, you truly believe in marriage.

57
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 And whether you get to know someone who is not good for you or anything, but you still have a hope, I can I can do it. I think that I have something in my heart that can be given to someone.

58
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:38,840
 Yeah. And I'm glad that you bring that up, actually, because this is a discussion that we have a lot in my home about the sacrament of marriage and really how important that sacrament is, because I think what happens is a lot of a lot of younger people and in this new generation, they they have forgotten and lost sight of the sacrament.

59
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:50,780
 And they're they're they're opting to get married outside of the church because it's more about a party and it's more about just the festivities of getting married versus the sacrament itself.

60
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:56,780
 And I think for me, I definitely was influenced by my parents commitment to their marriage.

61
00:09:56,780 --> 00:10:07,820
 It was it was broken. You know, it was there was a lot of brokenness in their marriage and lots of things that I wish, you know, had they had healed and worked on.

62
00:10:07,820 --> 00:10:18,820
 Right. But but I think the example of their commitment to their sacrament is what influenced me to knowing that one day I want what my mom and dad had,

63
00:10:18,820 --> 00:10:29,880
 which was the sacrament of sacrament of marriage and and take what was beautiful and and have that and then take what was not and fix it, you know.

64
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:40,980
 So where they didn't fix it, I want to be able to ensure that I have something better, but also still have the most important part, which is the sacrament of marriage.

65
00:10:41,440 --> 00:10:46,660
 You said that you had very abusive relationship with the father of your child.

66
00:10:46,660 --> 00:10:52,420
 And can you tell me, was it some kind of moment when you realized this?

67
00:10:52,420 --> 00:10:59,460
 It doesn't have any sense anymore or it was just a lot of things and you said, I'm done.

68
00:10:59,660 --> 00:11:01,620
 Yeah. So it was a lot of things.

69
00:11:01,620 --> 00:11:10,920
 And what was looking back, you know, I prayed a lot for him to change, for things to get better.

70
00:11:11,360 --> 00:11:22,240
 And what I realized is, you know, he had the free will to change and and God was saying to me, if he's not going to change, then you don't deserve this.

71
00:11:22,240 --> 00:11:23,980
 Right. That you you deserve better.

72
00:11:23,980 --> 00:11:35,460
 And so there came a moment, a final moment where I was humiliated at my job because I found out that he was, you know, cheating on me.

73
00:11:35,460 --> 00:11:38,440
 And and that was it.

74
00:11:38,440 --> 00:11:39,780
 I couldn't take any more.

75
00:11:39,780 --> 00:11:41,680
 You know, there was a physical abuse.

76
00:11:41,680 --> 00:11:45,600
 It was emotional abuse, verbal abuse, psychological abuse.

77
00:11:45,600 --> 00:11:47,800
 I mean, all the abuses, sexual abuse.

78
00:11:47,800 --> 00:11:49,720
 You know, I endured it all.

79
00:11:49,720 --> 00:11:56,880
 But I think that moment of humiliation, you know, in public is what just it was almost like eye opening.

80
00:11:56,880 --> 00:12:08,200
 And it was very interesting how it happened, because just a few weeks before that, I had just put myself on my knees and humbled myself before the Lord.

81
00:12:08,200 --> 00:12:14,200
 And I and instead of praying for change, I simply asked God.

82
00:12:14,200 --> 00:12:15,200
 And I still remember this.

83
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:33,980
 This has been a very long time ago, but I still remember praying and submitting myself and just asking the Lord to open my eyes to the truth that if I was not supposed to be in this relationship and if he wanted something more for me, just show me, reveal it to me in plain sight.

84
00:12:34,140 --> 00:12:38,600
 And then just a week or two later is when that was revealed to me.

85
00:12:38,600 --> 00:13:00,480
 And so I saw that as an answer to my prayer, as painful as it was, because I think for anyone who's in a very long relationship with someone that they love and they share a child with, you know, it is very painful to to come to the realization that it's all just, you know, for for nothing.

86
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:07,540
 And, you know, and I grieved the end of something that really just was never meant to be.

87
00:13:07,540 --> 00:13:22,100
 And but I but it was also such a huge blessing, because, again, if it had not been for her finally leaving and recognizing my own worth, you know, I would not have met my now husband of of 18 years.

88
00:13:22,480 --> 00:13:33,200
 And for those ladies who are out there and having also abusive relationship, can you tell me, did you just cut him out of your life?

89
00:13:33,200 --> 00:13:38,180
 Did you just grow and you say, no more of you in my life?

90
00:13:38,180 --> 00:13:39,560
 Or how was it?

91
00:13:39,560 --> 00:13:40,920
 Were you scared?

92
00:13:40,920 --> 00:13:44,200
 I'm sure they also are scared and everything.

93
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:53,800
 So how was the moment of leaving and traumatized, maybe scared if he's coming back for you for child threats or something like?

94
00:13:54,060 --> 00:13:56,480
 Yeah, so I, you know, it was interesting.

95
00:13:56,480 --> 00:14:04,400
 I think what it was, is I got to a point where I finally saw my worth and value in God's eyes.

96
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:17,760
 I think that was what was really the eye opening moment where for all of those years, when someone is verbally abusing you, when someone's always making you feel less than unworthy.

97
00:14:19,060 --> 00:14:27,700
 There's a lot of psychological abuse there that happens where you, that you think that you deserve it, you know, and, and that you don't deserve better.

98
00:14:27,700 --> 00:14:32,760
 And so you keep hanging on thinking it's going to change, it's going to get better, and it never does.

99
00:14:32,760 --> 00:14:42,400
 And for a little bit, it's good, you know, so you have these moments of beauty and wonderful times and fun times, and then you have the abuse.

100
00:14:42,400 --> 00:14:45,420
 And it's just an ongoing cycle that never ends.

101
00:14:45,420 --> 00:14:54,700
 And that, I think, just the one day, you know, God gave me this grace to realize that I deserved better than that.

102
00:14:54,700 --> 00:14:59,140
 And that if he truly loved me, then he wouldn't treat me this way.

103
00:14:59,720 --> 00:15:08,380
 And, and that's really where the courage came from to say enough and realizing that, okay, I'm going to walk away from this.

104
00:15:08,380 --> 00:15:23,040
 And if he really loves me, he will change and he'll work on himself, but he'll have to do that on his own to prove that he really, you know, loves me and his daughter and he wants this to work.

105
00:15:23,180 --> 00:15:24,220
 And he never did.

106
00:15:24,220 --> 00:15:28,900
 And so when he didn't do that, I realized it's just, this is not it.

107
00:15:28,900 --> 00:15:30,700
 This is not what God wants for me.

108
00:15:30,700 --> 00:15:32,260
 It's not what God wanted for me.

109
00:15:32,260 --> 00:15:33,540
 It's what I wanted for me.

110
00:15:33,540 --> 00:15:41,220
 I wasn't submitting my life to God's will, nor was I ever praying for the right man to come into my life.

111
00:15:41,220 --> 00:15:47,880
 But I was a child, you know, when we met, I was 16 years old, or I think I was 15 turning 16.

112
00:15:48,060 --> 00:15:53,840
 And when we met, so I was a child and I wasn't thinking, you know, like a woman.

113
00:15:53,840 --> 00:16:15,960
 And of course, having a child out of wedlock as a child, you feel stuck in that relationship and you don't really understand, you know, how to pray for a husband, how to be chased before marriage and, and understand how important those things are so that you can really understand who you're marrying.

114
00:16:15,960 --> 00:16:20,160
 And if that person that you're marrying really loves you for you.

115
00:16:20,160 --> 00:16:25,140
 And, and so that's what, that's what I left is, is just all of that.

116
00:16:25,140 --> 00:16:38,240
 And then met my husband and, and then I could see that, yes, this is, this is the man who is going to respect me, who's going to honor me, who's going to be faithful to me, and who's going to truly love me.

117
00:16:38,420 --> 00:16:45,620
 And he said yes to all of your life and to everything that you, he just accept all of that.

118
00:16:45,620 --> 00:16:45,940
 Yeah.

119
00:16:45,940 --> 00:16:51,360
 Well, I have had a daughter, you know, my daughter at the time that I met my husband, but he also had a daughter.

120
00:16:51,720 --> 00:16:55,660
 And he had also gone through some things too, you know, difficult things.

121
00:16:55,660 --> 00:17:03,160
 And I think that was what was really important is that we both understood each other and we both had been through some difficult times.

122
00:17:03,160 --> 00:17:25,660
 So we understood what it was like to be, to go through difficult relationships and to go through difficult moments and, and then to be able to come together and relate and share that and understand one another, to be able to accept one another for the mistakes that we made in our pasts and want something better for ourselves.

123
00:17:25,720 --> 00:17:33,920
 I loved when you said yesterday that you, you both didn't have a sacrament and you know that you want it.

124
00:17:33,920 --> 00:17:34,680
 Yes.

125
00:17:34,680 --> 00:17:35,400
 Yeah.

126
00:17:35,400 --> 00:17:37,460
 We, we, we grew up very similar.

127
00:17:37,460 --> 00:17:41,880
 Uh, he had baptism and communion.

128
00:17:41,880 --> 00:17:44,280
 So first he was, had, had his first communion.

129
00:17:44,280 --> 00:17:47,820
 I had not, um, but we were not confirmed in the church.

130
00:17:47,820 --> 00:17:55,680
 And so when we were engaged, we, um, went through, you know, RCIA, which is the right of Christian initiation for adults.

131
00:17:55,720 --> 00:18:02,020
 And the Catholic faith and to come fully into the church, um, so that we could get married in the Catholic church.

132
00:18:02,020 --> 00:18:10,820
 And, and although we, um, although we knew that was necessary for, you know, us to get married in the church.

133
00:18:10,820 --> 00:18:17,620
 And again, I think part of that was, you know, we had this longing and this desire to be married in the Catholic church.

134
00:18:17,620 --> 00:18:27,260
 Uh, we may not have really at that time understood, you know, what that meant in terms of living out our faith as a Catholic couple.

135
00:18:27,260 --> 00:18:32,240
 But there was this longing that we both had to be married in the Catholic church.

136
00:18:32,240 --> 00:18:37,120
 And, and thank God that we did because it's, it got us through some very difficult times.

137
00:18:37,120 --> 00:18:38,500
 That's so nice.

138
00:18:38,500 --> 00:18:39,680
 Thank you so much.

139
00:18:39,680 --> 00:18:42,140
 Planned Parenthood in your life.

140
00:18:42,140 --> 00:18:43,300
 How did you get in?

141
00:18:43,400 --> 00:18:44,540
 That's the difficult time.

142
00:18:44,540 --> 00:18:47,760
 That's the difficult time.

143
00:18:47,760 --> 00:18:48,220
 Yes.

144
00:18:48,220 --> 00:18:57,500
 So when my husband and I were married, uh, in 2006 and we, um, um, had our first child immediately,

145
00:18:57,500 --> 00:19:03,580
 we, we conceived our first child, uh, just a month after we were married, despite the fact

146
00:19:03,580 --> 00:19:07,060
 that doctors told me that I probably wouldn't be able to conceive.

147
00:19:07,740 --> 00:19:17,220
 And, um, and so we conceived our son a month after and when he was born premature and it was a pretty traumatic time for,

148
00:19:17,220 --> 00:19:18,140
 for both of us.

149
00:19:18,140 --> 00:19:19,060
 Yes, absolutely.

150
00:19:19,060 --> 00:19:25,700
 So I suffered from endometriosis for, I'm assuming, you know, all of my life.

151
00:19:25,700 --> 00:19:31,180
 And, um, I was really, really struggling, uh, with pain.

152
00:19:31,180 --> 00:19:38,100
 And when I went to see my physician, he wanted to do surgery to look inside and see, you know,

153
00:19:38,100 --> 00:19:38,760
 what was happening.

154
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:42,700
 And this was just right after my husband and I got married.

155
00:19:42,700 --> 00:19:50,980
 We were married in June of 2006 and had, I had the surgery, uh, in August and in July we

156
00:19:50,980 --> 00:19:54,600
 had conceived our son, but I didn't know that we were, that we had conceived.

157
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:00,660
 So we had our, I had my surgery, forgive me, I think it was July, July that I had my surgery

158
00:20:00,660 --> 00:20:04,860
 because we, he was conceived in July and then I had my surgery towards the end of July.

159
00:20:04,860 --> 00:20:10,540
 And, um, the doctor, you know, when I came in for my follow-up after the post-surgery,

160
00:20:10,540 --> 00:20:17,140
 the doctor had told me that I was, that endometriosis was everywhere, everywhere, uh, fallopian tubes,

161
00:20:17,140 --> 00:20:19,580
 you know, ovaries everywhere.

162
00:20:20,140 --> 00:20:26,080
 And he said it would probably be very difficult if at all possible for me to conceive naturally.

163
00:20:26,080 --> 00:20:32,880
 And my, I remember the conversation my husband and I had on the drive home after the, the appointment.

164
00:20:32,880 --> 00:20:38,020
 And, and I was really sad because I had hoped that my husband and I would have children together.

165
00:20:38,020 --> 00:20:48,780
 And, and we spoke about how, um, we wouldn't opt for any type of, you know, um, infertility treatments or anything like that.

166
00:20:48,860 --> 00:20:55,580
 I just, I had never really learned about the church's teaching on those things, but just instinctively,

167
00:20:55,580 --> 00:20:59,920
 I knew that if it was God's will for us to have children, that it would happen.

168
00:20:59,920 --> 00:21:02,660
 And if it wasn't, then we would just have to accept God's will.

169
00:21:02,660 --> 00:21:09,340
 And my husband agreed with me, you know, and, um, shortly after a few days later,

170
00:21:09,340 --> 00:21:15,900
 I would begin to feel sick and I was vomiting and, and I don't know why, but I just felt like

171
00:21:15,900 --> 00:21:17,280
 I should take a pregnancy test.

172
00:21:17,280 --> 00:21:23,100
 And so it turned out I was pregnant and I had already conceived, I had already conceived our

173
00:21:23,100 --> 00:21:23,500
 son.

174
00:21:23,500 --> 00:21:31,340
 Um, so I was pregnant during my surgery and did the doctors never saw it, never saw it,

175
00:21:31,340 --> 00:21:31,700
 never.

176
00:21:31,700 --> 00:21:36,480
 And so I called the doctor and I said, um, you know, I explained to him that my pregnancy

177
00:21:36,480 --> 00:21:42,840
 test was positive and the doctor was in shock and I heard him exclaim because I was on the

178
00:21:42,840 --> 00:21:47,580
 nurse, on the phone with the nurse and the nurse said, let me, let me talk to the doctor.

